# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

Successfully implemented Vercel Speed Insights for the Next.js portfolio website.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed Package
- Added `@vercel/speed-insights` (v1.3.1) to dependencies
- Used npm as the project's package manager
- Updated package-lock.json accordingly

### 2. Modified Files

**src/app/layout.tsx**
- Imported `SpeedInsights` component from `@vercel/speed-insights/next`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component inside the `<body>` tag after the existing `<Analytics />` component
- Preserved all existing code structure and functionality

**package.json**
- Added `@vercel/speed-insights` dependency

**package-lock.json**
- Updated with new dependency tree for Speed Insights package

## Implementation Details

This project uses Next.js 16.1.6 with App Router, which is newer than version 13.5, so the implementation followed the standard approach:
- Imported from `@vercel/speed-insights/next` (Next.js-optimized version)
- Placed the component in the root layout at `src/app/layout.tsx`
- No additional configuration needed - the component automatically tracks Core Web Vitals

The Speed Insights component is positioned alongside the existing Analytics component, following a consistent pattern for Vercel monitoring tools.

## Verification

✅ Build completed successfully with no errors
✅ Linter passed for the modified layout.tsx file
✅ Type checking passed during build
✅ All changes properly staged in git

## Notes

- The project already had `@vercel/analytics` installed, making this a natural addition
- Speed Insights will automatically track performance metrics when deployed to Vercel
- No additional configuration or environment variables required
- The component is lightweight and won't impact page performance
